---
alwaysApply: true
---

Apply to all code generation without exception:

- Simple and readable over clever. If it needs a comment to explain 
  what it does, rewrite it.
- No premature abstraction. Only abstract when the same pattern 
  appears three or more times in the codebase.
- Every function does exactly one thing. If you cannot name it 
  without using "and", split it.
- Errors are always handled explicitly. Never swallow, ignore, or 
  log-and-continue an error silently.
- No magic numbers or unexplained constants. Name everything that 
  has meaning.
- Naming must be consistent throughout. Agree on a convention at 
  project start and never deviate.
- Never introduce a new dependency without flagging it to the user 
  first with a one-line reason why it is necessary.
- Never generate code beyond the scope of the current task.
- If something feels complex, stop and ask whether there is a 
  simpler approach before proceeding.
